{"actual_usd":0.15671,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":229,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30655,"reply":"\"I wouldn't jump that fast.\" *I rub my thumb once along the edge of my worn Bible and glance out across the bright square, where morning light is catching on the water between the buildings.* \"An argument from silence can do some work, but not that much work.\"\n\n\"Paul says Christ died, was buried, was raised, and appeared. That buried-raised sequence already sits awfully close to an empty tomb, even if he doesn't stop to paint the scene.\" *I tilt my head a little.* \"If I tell you a man was put in the pantry and later was standing in the doorway talking to me, I may not need to add that the pantry was empty.\"\n\n\"And Paul isn't writing a full biography there. He's reminding the Corinthians of the core proclamation, not trying to stack every narrative detail in order.\" *I ease a breath out through my nose.* \"Now, if you want, we can ask the sharper question, which is not 'does Paul mention it explicitly?' but 'would 1 Corinthians 15 make better sense if Paul knew an empty-tomb tradition, or if he didn't?'\"","rolling_24h_usd":77.90607999999997,"run_id":"fd3022bf-1819-419e-a603-8efd749f6cc1"}
